\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:ModelDynamics"

\end_inset

Model Specification
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With the properties of the utility function discussed so far, we now discuss
 how the observed variables which the consumer evaluates to exercise her
 choice of quality that is turn measured as the distance from cost of basic
 needs.
 These observed variables are the i) needs of the consumer ii) her income
 and iii) the assets she owns.
 To measure the quality chosen by the consumer, we observe the consumption
 within certain categories (which for in the current chapter are food, energy,
 transport and household).
 These variables are then assimilated in the Euler equations of the intertempora
l substitution problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The additive form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon(\Psi,\nu,A)$
\end_inset

 means that there is a substitution between quality and assets.
 A consumer could achieve the same utility - inclusive of status - as that
 of a consumer with with higher education or higher asset ownership by raising
 her high-quality consumption.
 Similarly, the asset-owners need not purchase quality to stay ahead of
 others.
 Empirically, however, we note that high quality in non-durable often is
 constrained by asset ownership.
 Those who own a refrigerator spend less on kerosene for their energy needs
 compared to those who don't own a refrigerator.
 If we measure quality as the distance from cost of needs, there is a sunken
 cost the refrigerator owner incurs due to her asset ownership.
 If we wish to view quality after having conditioned for such costs in order
 to avoid double-counting the advantage the asset owner has, we ought to
 separate the quality demanded by the consumer from that which is incurred
 due to asset ownership.
 To ask whether the refrigerator owners spend more on exotic fruits than
 those those who don't, we must separate the running costs of the refrigerator
 from the measurement of quality control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Two measures address this standardisation of demand - first is the classificati
on of quality in separable commodities e.g.
 food, energy so that we may compare demand for quality in food with that
 for quality in household goods or transport.
 The second is the introduction of a cost-function 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 - which accounts for the cost of maintaining assets or similar characteristics
 (such as education or social class) 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is possible that ownership of some assets generates some rental income.
 Although we haven't found the significance of such income in the consumption
 data, we would prefer to treat such income as an additional stream of income
 instead treating it as negative costs in the model.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This takes care of the peer-effects to some extent - giving more weight
 to quality consumed by non-asset owners than would be if we didn't include
 the cost of assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:NeedsProcess"

\end_inset

Needs of the consumer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we have briefly discussed in the Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:nonstochproblem"

\end_inset

, our notion of quality is dependent on what we consider as needs rather
 than the characteristics of items (see Rosen
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RosenImplicitHedonic1974"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a summary of hedonic approaches).
 We define needs as the standard requirements not meeting which would lead
 to a definite harm (this is in accordance to the theory argued for by Doyal
 and Gough 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 To an argument that a family can survive on just starch, the counter-argument
 would be that a foreseeable damage to the health of the consumer incurred
 by not having other nutrients is definite - thus ruling out a starch diet
 fulfilling the set of dietary needs.
 However, such a theory of needs is a normative concern (rather than descriptive
) - as a consumer may not always want her needs.
 Such a model for needs cannot represent a situation where consumers forgo
 a certain need to compromise on their health or autonomy in favour of some
 other wants.
 This makes the task to ensure that the needs are indeed just a minimum
 necessary set for health and autonomy to the individual extremely important.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider the minimum requirements for commodities such as food, clothing,
 housing and employment and calculate the costs associated with them in
 the local context (at a district level in the Tanzanian data - for example).
 The cost of the basic requirements per head 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 thus calculated are then multiplied with the number of family members 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

 to obtain the cost of needs of the household (
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}\cdot\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

).
 Relying only on total costs associated with a commodity (i.e.
 without using the quantity consumed), this notion of quality cannot differentia
te between the consumption of a higher quantity and of a higher quality.
 Consider for example, a household with a single member having consuming
 the quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}$
\end_inset

 for a commodity priced 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 If the minimum requirement for basic needs is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi=p_{1}q_{0}$
\end_inset

, then our quality metric for the consumer is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{p_{1}q_{1}}{p_{1}q_{0}}=\frac{q_{1}}{q_{0}}$
\end_inset

.
 For the individual's household, consuming more quantity than the minimum
 may increase the measure of quality much the way it would if she had switched
 to a better quality.
 As the consumption surveys often don't record the quantity consumed for
 non-food commodities e.g.
 clothing, toiletries etc.
 (nor the associated brand information), there is no way for us to distinguish
 between over-consumption and high-quality consumption by relying solely
 on the total consumption on the good (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p\cdot q=\sum_{i}p_{i}q_{i}=x$
\end_inset

).
 However, as we do know whether the range of goods within a commodity are
 available in the region or not, it may be possible to draw conclusions
 about over-consumption and higher-quality consumption for a group of consumers
 - separated by region or other characteristics - who face different ranges
 of goods available within a commodity.
 This is particularly so when using pseudo-panel analyses for the data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Whether we model the needs of the household as a unit that lives forever
 (dynasty) or as a household individual with a finite lifetime 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, the evolution of needs as the number of living family members at a certain
 period must be aligned with the population trends in the economy.
 In the particular context of a developing country, we find that the expected
 path of needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(t,T)$
\end_inset

 is influenced with a high population growth rate and prevalence of a joint-fami
ly structure.
 Based on the data observed in the sub-Saharan African countries, we consider
 the functional form 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(t,T)=\mathbbm{1}_{t<T}\mu te^{-\kappa t^{2}}$
\end_inset

 to map the age 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 of the household head to the expected value of number of members of the
 household at time time (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta(t,T)$
\end_inset

).
 We assume that this trajectory of needs is known to the consumer and that
 she adjusts her consumption according to this trajectory.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Income Process
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
The goal of using an income process in the model is to provide an exogenous
 way to differentiate increase in household incomes from the accumulation
 of assets.
 It is the substitution of the latter with consumption that is crucial to
 our interpretation of status consumption as a quality scale.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike in PIH, we hope that accumulaton of long-term assets have an influence
 on the subsitution between savings and quality.
