\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the variables needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

, owned assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

, income 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 and observed consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 that are observed in the data, we now turn to a quality control in the
 Euler equations of the intertemporal setting that represents the consumer
 choice for quality.
 By definition of the needs, a consumer is meant to select a quality control
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 only after her needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

 and those imposed by the owned assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and her personal characteristics 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 are fulfilled (the lack of subscript in 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is due to the assumption that the personal characteristics don't change
 in the near-term analysis).
 Thus we view the quality control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 (in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) as a multiplier of the cost of needs - the higher its value the higher
 would be the distance from the basic needs consumption (and lower would
 be the future growth of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
One could also introduce some inertia for quality in the model by considering
 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{w}$
\end_inset

 a long-term habit of the consumer that remains the same over the period
 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Other than the control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

, the consumption depends both on needs and the long-term choices of the
 consumer (which are encapsulated by the asset 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 the consumer has accumulated in the past and the the personal characteristics
 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 she possesses).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-durable costs imposed by the assets one possesses (e.g.
 fuel for cars, electricity for heating equipment, rent/maintenance-fees
 for housing etc.) imply either that avoiding the respective expenses is
 not an option for the consumer owning some assets or that some certain
 long-term choices or characteristics (e.g.
 not having a house or living in a region that doesn't have electricity
 available) would limit the choice to avail quality through non-durable
 consumption.
 For example, a homeowner is required to maintain her own house the way
 someone who doesn't own the house has to pay the rent.
 As some costs are incurred due to the assets that the consumer acquires,
 a distance from the basic needs (which are themselves imposed only by health
 and autonomy requirements) could be introduced as the consumer acquires
 more assets.
 Such 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

enhanced
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 needs of the consumer as she acquires assets necessitate a parameter in
 the model that is different from the quality control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 and separates how much the consumer choice is related to her long-term
 standing influenced by 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 from how much quality is demanded in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 This former constraint is provided with the cost-function 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 - which along with the quality control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 selected by the consumer contributes to the consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 thus adjusts the non-durable consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 with the costs incurred due to asset ownership (e.g.
 of maintenance fees or rent in the housing example).
 The Euler equations for this model are as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{gather}
\eta_{t}=\eta(t,T)\nonumber \\
A_{t+1}=A_{t}+(i_{t+1}-c_{t+1})\nonumber \\
i_{t+1}=ki_{t}\nonumber \\
c_{t+1}=(1+\nu_{t+1})\Psi_{t}\eta_{t}+p(A_{t},\rho)\label{eq:nonstoch}
\end{gather}

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

 represents the consumer need unit at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

