\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

) based on 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given the observed variables 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t},A_{t},\rho,i_{t},\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

, the consumer optimises the non-stochastic sum 
\begin_inset Formula $u=\sum_{i=1}^{T}\upsilon(\nu_{i},A_{i},\rho_{i})$
\end_inset

 over her life-time of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 years.
 The consumer chooses 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t+1}\ge0$
\end_inset

 in period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to consume the quality she desires.
 The minimum cost for maintaining the needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

 in the period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 are meant to be chosen by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu=0$
\end_inset

.
 Assuming a log-linear form of the utility 
\begin_inset Formula $\upsilon$
\end_inset

, the consumer optimises 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}(\alpha\nu_{i}+\beta\cdot ln\ A_{i}+(1-\alpha-\beta)\cdot ln\ \rho_{i})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 are constants.
 Notice that since additivity discourages substitution, the low substitution
 between 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 makes the combined utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\upsilon(\nu_{i},A_{i},\rho_{i})$
\end_inset

 plausible 
