\begin_layout Standard
Needs are related to consumption 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{t}$
\end_inset

 through their cost in the particular locality where the household is located.
 Given the categories of consumption in Tanzania i.e.
 food, household, energy and transport, we calculate the cost of basic needs
 as the cost a minimal requirements in every category.
 As an example, we use the commodity sub-groups of carbohydrates, fat, protein
 and fruits-vegetables in the food category.
 The cost of this minimal basket - which is composed of the recommended
 nutrient quantities - are then calculated in each region and district based
 on the prices of the items recorded in the survey (which records the prices
 at the district level as well).
 For most regions, as it turns out, this minimum-cost basket could be a
 diet of cassava, cooking-oil, eggs and bananas - as these are most often
 the cheapest items in their respective sub-group (
\begin_inset Formula ${carb,fact,protein,fruitsveg}$
\end_inset

).
 As one would expect, the cost of this basket thus calculated is much higher
 in the urban areas than in the rural areas (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:BasketsRegions2010"

\end_inset

) .
 Using a similar treatment for energy category, we find that the minimum
 requirements would be met for consumers in Tanzania with kerosene - given
 its ubiquity and comparatively low price with respect to sparsely available
 electricity in the country.
 Here, a calorie quota for a the preparation of a typical meal and lighting
 is used - leading us to use the cost of a certain amount of kerosene (or
 a cheaper alternative) when available.
 For household, the cost of the minimal house in the locality (amortised
 over the average working life) and the cost of clothing per year is used.
 For transport, we use public-transport costs and petrol consumption costs
 depending on where the consume resides and whether the consumer owns a
 car or not.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate the income process, we use the reported income from primary
 occupations in the Tanzania LSMS data over the years 2010, 2012 and 2014.
 One limitation of the Tanzanian LSMS data is that it does not provide income
 data for every household head for which the consumption diary and assets
 are recorded.
 Another limitation of the data set is that a household that is visited
 in a particular year is less likely to be visited after more than 2 years.
 This means that while a significant number households would be common between
 2010 and 2012 as well as between 2012 and 2014, very few households that
 were visited in 2010 would be visited the third time in 2014 (in fact less
 than 100 household from the survey in 2010 seem to be visited in 2014 for
 income survey).
 Such a lack of a true panel data compels us to prepare a pseudo-panel for
 the calibration of the income process.
 The pseudo-panel we prepare is based on the similarity of the number of
 adults, the number of children, the year of birth of the adults, the occupation
 and education levels
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A minor issue encountered while the preparation of the pseudo-panel related
 to the age of the household members was circumvented with an approximate
 matching of that year-of-birth values.
 The LSMS community survey appears to have recorded the year-of-birth values
 for individuals in years 2010 and 2012 but the age variable is recorded
 instead for the year 2014.
 Matching the year-of-birth values from 2012 with the YOB values inferred
 from the recorded age was made possible by allowing a tolerance for matching
 the YOB values for the preparation of the pseudo-panel.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Since the Hausman tests point to the inconsistency of the RE Gestimator
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 , we use a FE GLS estimator for the pseudo-panel.
 That said, we do favour the use of RE estimator when the effect of time-invaria
nt cross-sectional variables are considered important (see Bell et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BellJonesFECrossSection2015"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a discussion).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand how the function 
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset


\series default
 may be fitted with empirical data, consider a set of items say 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0},I_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{2}$
\end_inset

 over which the quality control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 is selected by the consumer.
 The items 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0},I_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{3}$
\end_inset

 have prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0},p_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2}$
\end_inset

 respectively so that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}<p_{1}<p_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

 is the item with the lowest available quality (hence the minimum price
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

).
 Assuming that the quantity needed for minimum needs per head is 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

, two consumers 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 choosing 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{10}q_{11})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{20},q_{22})$
\end_inset

 - where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{ij}$
\end_inset

 is quantity consumed of item 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 by the consumer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 - would effectively set 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\nu_{1}p_{0}=\sum_{k=0}^{2}p_{k}q_{1k}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta p_{0}\nu_{2}=\sum_{k=0}^{2}p_{k}q_{2k}$
\end_inset

.
 The value of the control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{i\in[1,2]}$
\end_inset

 represents merely the distance from the fulfillment of the basic needs
 i.e.
 the cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta p_{0}$
\end_inset

 and represents the consumer preference for quality within a certain commodity.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The form of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nonstoch"

\end_inset

 follows from this basic view of quality control.
 Consider a consumer facing only the prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 for item 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

, so that all items other than the item 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{0}$
\end_inset

 have been removed from her basket (or the market accessible to her).
 The likely effect of having just the quantity consumed as 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{10}$
\end_inset

 is thus be to reduce 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

 (since 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{k=0}^{2}p_{k}q_{1k}=p_{0}q_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}<p_{1}<p_{2}$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Notice however, that the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{1}\ge1$
\end_inset

 still applies.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The effect of having constraints on quality due to 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is thus equivalent to addition or removal of items from the consumer basket.
 If a rural consumer who has access to only some of the items from the urban
 basket (which an urban consumer has access to), the quality control 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 she chooses is equivalent to removing some items from the urban consumer's
 basket.
 Thus the function 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 can also be seen as a filter on the set of prices of a basket of all items
 (i.e.
 items available at a national level or at the respective top level of granulari
ty in an empirical) that returns the costs pertinent to owned asset level
 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 and a certain 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Equivalently, when the consumer acquires more assets, her basket effectively
 expands as she is forced to be away from basic needs consumption cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta p_{0}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Potentially, the effects of regional variation in the basket (more items
 within a commodity) on the varied consumption of 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu$
\end_inset

 can also be accommodated with 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 by treating the additional expenditure on quality in an expensive region
 - where the basket is more varied - as a cost.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
While this approach hasn't been followed in our empirical analyses, the
 filter 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 can be used to standardise the supply conditions in a more general analysis
 - e.g.
 in a comparison of demand between two disparate economies.
 For example, in the more developed market, one expects to see rental options,
 availability of cheaper substitutes or extension of credit facilities to
 the consumer for an durable good that is too expensive for her.
 This contrast in the supply conditions would have two effects on the consumer
 demand.
 First, the difference between successive asset costs in an order of assets
 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{i}=A_{i}-A_{i-1}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula ${A_{i}}={A_{1}<A_{2}<A_{3}}$
\end_inset

) would be lower in the more developed market because the market would make
 cheaper alternatives available to the consumer.
 Second, a lot of assets can be availed without ownership in the developed
 market.
 To consider a particular example of car ownership, we would see both that
 the cars can be enjoyed with a frequent non-durable cost (rental) rather
 than through ownership and that the cars are available in a wider range
 of costs in the developed market.
 Standardsing the supply conditions in the two economies with 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 would imply a less discrete distribution of assets in the developed market
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta A_{t}$
\end_inset

 ) so that the same level of 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

 may correspond to a higher 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho$
\end_inset

) in the developed market.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

, one may use either the form involving 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ModelDynamics"

\end_inset

 or plugin the costs associated with assets that are observed in the consumption
 diary directly as the output of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

.
 A sound definition of long-term assets and an appropriate form of 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 is necessary - as both the approaches are susceptible to measurement errors
 associated with the ownership and inter-generational transfer of assets.
 Empirically, we determine a long-term asset for the particular household
 as any good that has an expected lifetime long enough to be passed on to
 the owner's progeny.
 Recall that based on the arguments in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:LiteratureReview"

\end_inset

, a good that can't be passed on isn't long-term for the purposes of the
 current model and would not cause any observable change in the expected
 social mobility.
 Such consumption (inclusive of any status consumption through quality)
 is considered non-durable for our purposes and would not serve as an input
 to the process 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 - which returns only maintenance fees, rents or running costs associated
 with the ownership of long-term assets or maintenance of a certain characterist
ics (e.g.
 educational level, club membership etc.
 The costs such as maintenance fees or running costs can only contribute
 indirectly to the consumer's status-utility through the ownership of assets
 that impose such the costs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To infer the non-durable costs incurred from assets (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t}.\rho)$
\end_inset

 ), we also use the average operation for some of the assets.
 For example, a refrigerator - which is expected to run 24 hrs a day - would
 have a different electricity requirement and hence the running costs compared
 to an electrical stove or agricultural equipment which is used less sparingly.
 On the other hand, the running costs for entertainment boats or musical
 equipment - whose running time is controlled by the user and is associated
 with leisure - are not considered part of the quality constraint.
 Other than the assets 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{t}$
\end_inset

, the price filter 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

 also depends on the personal characteristics which may impose a certain
 lifestyle or habit on the consumer.
 For example, the consumers living in a remote area may have a zero consumption
 for certain commodities (
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)=0$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 for a certain values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These discrete effects cannot be modeled when using the approximation of
 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t-1},\rho)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $mA_{t}^{a}$
\end_inset

 in Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nonstochll"

\end_inset

 (as is done in the particular function for the solution discussed in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ModelDynamics"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, for the estimation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha/\beta$
\end_inset

, we consider a simple sum of quality control variables across commodities.
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 commodities (e.g.
 food, energy etc.), if we have 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1,t}=(1+\nu_{1,t})\eta_{t}\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2,t}=(1+\nu_{2,t})\eta_{t}\Psi_{t}$
\end_inset

, we use :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
c_{t}=\sum_{k=1}^{N}c_{k,t}=(\eta_{t}\Psi_{t})\sum_{k=1}^{N}\nu_{k,t}\label{eq:quality_sum}
\end{alignat}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every household thus responds to the common needs differently by adjusting
 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\nu_{t,k}\}$
\end_inset

.
 While it is possible to evaluate the model in Equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:nonstochll"

\end_inset

 for different commodity categories (i.e.
 using 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},\nu_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{2},\nu_{2}$
\end_inset

 etc.) - we estimate the aggregate 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{t}=\sum_{k=1}^{N}\nu_{t,k}$
\end_inset

 in the solution of the dynamic optimisation to explore how overall quality
 may evolve in an intertemporal setting under given 
\begin_inset Formula $p(A_{t},\rho)$
\end_inset

, income process 
\begin_inset Formula $i_{t}$
\end_inset

 and expected growth of needs 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

